<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06292245 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06292245 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  VIDEO; COMPANY; GAMBLING; GAME; END  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  State lottery officials Thursday abandoned a pilot project that would have letMinnesotans be the first in the nation to bet at home using Nintendo videogames.;   Many state legislators had opposed the project, saying it wouldentice children to gamble.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  NINTENDO LOTTERY PLAN SCRAPPED  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Lottery Director George Andersen defended the plan but conceded that&quot;legitimate issues raised by legislative policy makers call for extensivediscussion.&quot;;   The six-month test would have let 10,000 residents play athome starting next summer. Under the plan, players would choose numbers usingthe control deck from a Nintendo game and hook up via a modem to the lottery'scomputer system.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Minneapolis  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911018  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  6A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  103  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday, October 18, 199100292245,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>